body:
@r39132 I've made the changes to TriggerDagRunOperator. To clarify your comment about unique index violations, there is an issue where if you try to run the same dag with the same exact execution_date, you get an error because it inserts the run into the database using the dag_id and execution_date as a key.

sqlalchemy.exc.InvalidRequestError: This Session's transaction has been rolled back due to a previous exception during flush. To begin a new transaction with this Session, first issue Session.rollback(). Original exception was: (_mysql_exceptions.IntegrityError) (1062, "Duplicate entry 'example_trigger_target_dag-2015-01-01 00:00:00' for key 'dag_id'") [SQL: u'INSERT INTO dag_run (dag_id, execution_date, start_date, end_date, state, run_id, external_trigger, conf) VALUES (%s, %s, now(), %s, %s, %s, %s, %s)'] [parameters: ('example_trigger_target_dag', datetime.datetime(2015, 1, 1, 0, 0), None, u'running', 'trig__2015-01-01T00:00:00', 1, '\x80\x02}q\x01U\x07messageq\x02U\x0bHello Worldq\x03s.')]

Is this what you were referencing? Would this be considered an acceptable limitation or should I look into ways to fix this, maybe add something like a nonce to the dag_id to make the it unique?
